This avoids pre-checking `Value` by converting them into `Key` and (eventually) cloning the entire contents of a map when iterating over it.

This can only be merged once rust-lang/hashbrown#456 resolves and is released or an alternative solution is found.

This allows for any type which implements `HASH` and `EQ` to be used in a map. Including floats assuming they only normal or subnormal values that can be rectified:

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;

pub fn main() {
    let map = HashMap::new();
    map.insert(1.0, 2.0);
    map.insert(0.0, 3.0);
    dbg!(map);
    dbg!(map[1.0]);
    dbg!(map.get(-0.0));
    dbg!(map[0.0]);
}
```

```
{1.0: 2.0, 0.0: 3.0}
2.0
Some(3.0)
3.0
```

This is necessary to avoid unsound use of references in registered functions. An issue that was discovered when investigating #600.

The way function arguments are currently modeled uses unbound references, which among other things allow you to register a `'static` reference or any associated lifetime allowing values to escape:

```rust
#[rune::function]
fn download(url: &'static str) {
    todo!()
}

struct Foo<'a> {
    url: &'a str,
}

impl<'a> Foo<'a> {
    fn download(url: &'a str) {
        self.url = url;
    }
}

let module = Module::new();
module.function_meta(download);
```

With this change, functions like the above are correctly rejected instead. A downside is that we can no longer use references for arguments in async functions. Instead these must use owned types:

```rust
#[rune::function]
async fn download(url: &str) {
}
```
Becomes:
```rust
#[rune::function]
async fn download(url: Ref<str>) {
}
```
And associated types like this:
```rust
struct Foo;

impl Foo {
    #[rune::function]
    async fn download(&self, url: &str) {
    }
}
```
Becomes:
```rust
struct Foo;

impl Foo {
    #[rune::function(instance, path = Self::download)]
    async fn download(this: Ref<Self>, url: Ref<str>) {
    }
}
```

Add preliminary support for building and loading byte-code into the Vm from raw bytes, instead of having instructions always being an array of `Vec<Inst>`.

This has the potential of greatly reducing the size of Rune programs, but it comes with a performance penalty because instructions have to be decoded as they're being executed.

By default, we're still using the old array-based instructions format.

See the difference in in-memory size for the following program:

```rust
use std::iter::range;

pub fn main() {
    let it = range(0, 1000);
    let tail = 77;

    'label:
    while true {
        let value = 10;

        for n in it {
            loop {
                let value2 = 20;
                break 'label;
            }

            tail = tail + 1;
        }

        tail = tail + 1;
    }

    tail
}
```

Byte-code version: `196 bytes`.
Instruction array: `2560 bytes`.

This change introduces two major differences:

Entries in modules and contexts are ordered according to their insertion order. This means that:
* Errors generated from them will always be consistent, like for context errors where an item is ambiguous.
* Documentation generated will always list items in their declaration order.

The second large change is that the way generics are looked up has changed. Previously looking up a free generic method wouldn't fail until runtime. Now when possible it will fail at compile time instead. Note that generic functions can only be defined in native contexts.

Additional changes:

Deriving `Any` now requires that you specify the correct item the type belongs to. Its item must correspond to the module it's being installed in.

```rust
#[derive(Any)]
#[rune(item = ::process)]
struct Process {
    /* .. */
}

fn install() -> Result<rune::Module, rune::ContextError> {
    let mut module = rune::Module::with_crate("process");
    module.ty::<Process>()?;
    Ok(module)
}
```

Macros now take paths and identifiers instead of strings, so this:
* `#[rune(name = "Foo")]` is `#[rune(name = Foo)]`.
* `#[rune(install_with = "path::to::function")]` is `#[rune(name = path::to::function)]`.
* `#[rune(module = "rune2")]` is now `#[rune(module = rune2)]`.
